Installing Prometheus for Monitoring OpenShift Container Platform

Setting up Prometheus

Prometheus and its related components can be set up completely on top of OpenShift. A set of templates is provided.

  1. Log into your OpenShift Bastion Host and switch to the root user.

  2. Clone the repository containing all the Prometheus setup code:

    cd /root
git clone https://github.com/wkulhanek/openshift-prometheus
cd openshift-prometheus

  3. Create a new OpenShift Project to hold all Prometheus and related components:

    oc new-project prometheus --display-name="Prometheus Monitoring"

  4. Starting with OpenShift 3.6 the OpenShift routers expose a metrics endpoint on port 1936. For Prometheus to be able to monitor the routers this port needs to be open.

    Execute the following command to open the port on the nodes:

    ansible-playbook ./update_firewall.yml

  5. The router also requires basic authentication to be allowed to scrape the metrics. Find the router password by executing the following command:

    oc set env dc router -n default --list|grep STATS_PASSWORD|awk -F"=" '{print $2}'

  6. Execute the following command to instantiate the Prometheus template using the previously retrieved router password as a parameter:

    oc new-app -f prometheus.yaml --param ROUTER_PASSWORD=<Router Password>

  7. While Prometheus is deploying take a moment to examine the Prometheus template in the file prometheus.yaml. Note the following:

    • Prometheus runs under its own service account - and this service account is granted cluster-reader permission.

    • The Prometheus service includes annotations (prometheus.io/scrape: "true" and prometheus.io/scheme: http) that allow Prometheus to monitor itself.

    • Prometheus uses a persistent volume claim to store data.

    • There are two Config Maps to configure Prometheus itself as well as alerting rules. Based on your requirements you will want to customize these configurations.

      • The first Config Map (prometheus) contains the entire Prometheus configuration. Note how it contains a section to point to rules for alerting. The second Config Map (prometheus-rules) is mounted in that location.

      • Note how the configuration sets up the various scrape_config sections to identify targets for Prometheus.

Setting up Node Exporter

  1. Prometheus is able to self-discover an amazing array of information. In order for Prometheus to display Node and Docker metrics however it is necessary to deploy the Node Exporter. The node exporter runs as a DaemonSet to guarantee each node runs at least one copy of the application.

    Note
    		 Note that to be able to deploy a DaemonSet and set the right permissions for the pods your OpenShift user needs cluster-admin authorization.

  2. Switch to the node-exporter directory and run an Ansible playbook to open port 9100 on every node in the cluster:

    cd /root/openshift-prometheus/node-exporter
ansible-playbook -i /etc/ansible/hosts update_firewall.yml

  3. Since the node exporter will be accessing resources from each host, the service account being used to run the pod must be granted elevated access. Execute the following command to add the default Service Account in the prometheus project to the privileged SCC:

    oc adm policy add-scc-to-user privileged system:serviceaccount:prometheus:default

  4. Most OpenTLC environments include a default project node selector. This default node selector prevents the DaemonSet from placing pods on Masters and Infranodes. Therefore it is necessary to set an empty node selector for the prometheus project:

    oc annotate namespace prometheus openshift.io/node-selector=""

  5. Deploy the DaemonSet:

    oc project prometheus
oc new-app -f node-exporter.yaml

  6. While the node exporter already provides a wealth of information about each node we would like to get specific information about Docker and the Docker Volume Group. The repository contains a few scripts that run on each node to collect this information.

  7. Switch to the directory containing the dockerinfo scripts and run an Ansible Playbook to distribute the script to all nodes and set up a cron job to execute the script in regular intervals:

    cd /root/openshift-prometheus/node-exporter/dockerinfo
ansible-playbook -i /etc/ansible/hosts install_dockerinfo.yml

This concludes setting up the Prometheus infrastructure.

Verifying the Prometheus installation

To verify that Prometheus is set up properly navigate to the route that has been created for Prometheus and run a few sample queries.

  1. In your web browser navigate to the targets page of your Prometheus server (replace the route before /target with your specific route):

    1. http://prometheus-prometheus.apps.mon.example.opentlc.com/targets

  2. You should see the state UP in green next to every single endpoint. Note that there are 4 kinds of endpoints at the moment. Kubernetes includes built in support for Prometheus - and you will see the kubernetes-node-exporter endpoints for all of your nodes - the number should match the number of kubernetes-nodes endpoints.

  3. Switch to the Graph tab and try a few prometheus queries.

  4. In the Expression text box type

    node_docker_running_containers

    Then press Enter. You will see the number of running docker containers for each node.

  5. Now try a few Node specific queries (these come from the OpenShift node service itself):

    • node_memory_MemTotal

    • node_memory_MemFree

    • node_cpu

      Note
      		 Note how very detailed information about CPU is returned. To limit the CPU information to just the user mode you can limit the query to just that label: node_cpu {mode="user"}

  6. How about some individual container metrics:

    • container_memory_usage_bytes

    • container_cpu_usage_seconds_total

    • container_network_receive_bytes_total

  7. Check the other metrics that our dockerinfo script provides to our node exporters:

    • node_docker_volume_size_bytes

    • node_docker_volume_data_percent_full

    • node_docker_volume_meta_percent_full

Feel free to play around with queries and examine all available metrics from the drop-down box next to the Execute button. Also feel free to switch from Console to Graph to show the results of a query in (a rather simple) graphical fashion.

Grafana Dashboards

The volume of information in Prometheus can be overwhelming. Therefore it is much nicer to present the users with beautiful, graphical dashboards.

Luckily there is an open source Dashboard software called Grafana that can display data from Prometheus - as well as a number of other systems.

We can deploy Grafana easily alongside Prometheus.

  1. On your bastion host make sure you are in the prometheus project and create the Grafana deployment:

    oc project prometheus
oc new-app -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/wkulhanek/docker-openshift-grafana/master/grafana.yaml
oc get route grafana

  2. Once you know your Grafana route (usually similar to grafana-prometheus.apps.mon.example.opentlc.com) navigate to it in your web browser.

  3. Configure a Grafana Data Source

    • Log into Grafana using default account admin with password admin (maybe it would be a good idea to change the password after this…​).

    • On the Home Dashboard click Add data source

    • Use the following values for the datasource Config:

      • Name: DS-Prometheus

      • Type: Prometheus

      • Url: Route to your prometheus without a trailing /. E.g. http://prometheus-prometheus.apps.mon.example.opentlc.com

      • Access: direct

    • Click Add

    • Click Save & Test. You should see a message that the data source is working.

  4. Configure a Grafana Dashboard

    • There is an example dashboard JSON file openshift-metrics-dashboard.json available in the repository. This dashboard depends on metrics that are being collected by Prometheus as configured in previous steps of the lab.

      • There are more example dashboards available at https://grafana.com/dashboards?search=kubernetes.

    • Download the following Dashboard json file to your computer:

      cd $HOME
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/wkulhanek/docker-openshift-grafana/master/openshift-metrics-dashboard.json

    • In Grafana select the Icon on the top left and then select Dashboards / Import.

    • Either copy/paste the contents of the JSON File you just downloaded (make sure to keep the correct formatting) or click the Upload .json File button selecting the .json file from your $HOME directory.

    • In the next dialog enter OpenShift Metrics as the name and select the previously created datasource DS-Prometheus for Prometheus.

    • Click Import

    • You should see your dashboard with metrics coming from Prometheus:

Next Steps

Feel free to play around in the Grafana Dashboard or to investigate some of the queries behind the graphs.

If you hover over a graph a box appears at the top where you can click Edit to bring up the dashboard widget editor.

You can also try to import some pre-build Kubernetes Dashboards from https://grafana.com/dashboards?search=kubernetes (just be aware that some data these dashboards expect may not be available in our specific prometheus installation). :scrollbar: :data-uri: :toc2: :course_name: Red Hat OpenShift Operations

Alerting with Rocket Chat

Setting up Rocket Chat on top of OpenShift

Rocket Chat is an open source chat platform similar to Slack. We can easily deploy it on top of OpenShift and use it as an example of how to receive alerts from Prometheus in case things go wrong.

  1. Log back into the Shell on your Bastion host.

  2. Create a new project to hold our Rocket Chat instance:

    oc new-project rocketchat --display-name="Rocket Chat"

  3. Deploy a persistent MongoDB Database to hold our Rocket Chat configuration:

    oc new-app mongodb-persistent -p MONGODB_USER=rocketchat-admin -p MONGODB_PASSWORD=rocketchat -p MONGODB_DATABASE=rocketchat -p VOLUME_CAPACITY=4Gi

  4. Wait until the MongoDB Pod has fully initialized.

  5. Deploy the Rocket Chat image from DockerHub and connect it to the MongoDB database that we just created. Also expose the Rocket Chat service as a route.

    oc new-app docker.io/rocketchat/rocket.chat:latest -e MONGO_URL=mongodb://rocketchat-admin:rocketchat@mongodb:27017/rocketchat
oc expose svc rocketchat

  6. Monitor your pods and wait until Rocket Chat has fully started. You may want to tail the Pod logs to be sure.

  7. Rocket Chat uses a domain check code to verify the validity of the e-mail address. Since we don’t have any e-mail providers available we need to disable this check. To disable it, open a rsh session into your MongoDB pod (use oc get pod to find the specific name of your MondoDB pod - it will be something like mongodb-1-mgvb2):

    oc rsh <mongodb_pod>

  8. Once inside your MongoDB pod connect to the database:

    mongo localhost:27017

  9. One by one enter the following commands:

    use rocketchat
db.auth('rocketchat-admin','rocketchat')
db.rocketchat_settings.update({_id:'Accounts_UseDNSDomainCheck'},{$set:{value:false}})
exit

  10. Type exit and hit Enter to disconnect from your MondoDB pod.

Configuring Rocket Chat

  1. Determine the URL of your Rocket Chat instance:

    oc get route rocketchat

  2. In a web browser navigate to the Rocket Chat URL

  3. Select Register a new account (under the blue Login button)

  4. On the warning dialog click Yes

  5. When prompted to register User Name, update the suggestion or keep default and click Use this username.

  6. In order to have a place for the Alertmanager to send alerts we need to create a channel in Rocket Chat.

  7. Next to the Search box under your name click +

  8. Use openshift-alerts as the channel name and click Create

    We will configure this channel with an incoming web hook to receive alerts from the Alertmanager.

  9. Create the inbound web hook for the new channel

    1. Next to your user name click the down arrow

    2. Select Administration

    3. Click on Integrations

    4. Click on New Integration

    5. Click on Incoming WebHook

      • Enabled: True

      • Name: OpenShift Alerts

      • Post to Channel: #openshift-alerts

      • Post as: rocket.cat

      • Alias: Prometheus

      • Script Enabled: True

      • Copy and paste the script below into the Script box:

        class Script {
  process_incoming_request({
    request
  }) {
    var alertColor = "warning";
    var alertKind  = "UNDEFINED";

    if (request.content.status == "resolved") {
      alertColor = "good";
      alertKind  = "RESOLVED"
    } else if (request.content.status == "firing") {
      alertColor = "danger";
      alertKind  = "PROBLEM"
    }
    console.log(request.content);

    let finFields = [];
    for (i = 0; i < request.content.alerts.length; i++) {
      var endVal = request.content.alerts[i];
      var elem = {
        title: alertKind + ": " + endVal.labels.alertname,
        value: "Instance: " + endVal.labels.instance + "; " + "Description: " + endVal.annotations.description + "; " + "Summary: " + endVal.annotations.summary,
        short: false
      };

      finFields.push(elem);
    }
    return {
      content: {
        username: "Alertmanager",
        attachments: [{
          color: alertColor,
          title_link: request.content.externalURL,
          title: "Prometheus notification",
          fields: finFields,
        }]
      }
    };

    return {
      error: {
        success: false,
        message: 'Error accepting Web Hook'
      }
    };
  }
}

    6. Click Save Changes

    7. Copy the Webhook URL (this field only appears after clicking Save Changes) - we will need this URL later in order to configure our Alertmanager.

  10. Click x next to Administration to go back to the chat window

  11. From a shell prompt test that your web hook is working by sending an example JSON Payload to Rocket Chat replacing <WEBHOOK_URL> with the URL you copied down before:

    curl -X POST -H 'Content-Type: application/json' --data '{"alerts": [{"status": "testing", "labels": {"alertname": "alert_test", "instance": "instance.my.test.cluster" },   "annotations": { "description": "Alert Test Description",      "summary": "Alert Test Summary" } }]}' <WEBHOOK_URL>

  12. You should receive an Alert Message in your Rocket Chat Channel.

Install Alertmanager

Now that we have a target to receive our alerts we can configure the Alertmanager to send alerts when things go wrong.

  1. Back on your Bastion Host switch to the directory with the Alertmanager code. Also make sure you are back in the Prometheus OPenShift project.

    cd /root/openshift-prometheus/alertmanager
oc project prometheus

  2. Create the Alertmanager replacing <WEBHOOK_URL> with the previously copied web hook URL:

    oc new-app -f alertmanager.yaml -p VOLUME_CAPACITY=4Gi -p WEBHOOK_URL=<WEBHOOK_URL>

  3. You can see the configuration of the Alertmanager by examining the ConfigMap that has been created by the template:

    oc get cm alertmanager -o yaml

    At the end of the file you will see the section that configures the Alertmanager to send the alert to a web hook:

    receivers:
- name: 'webhook'
  webhook_configs:
  - send_resolved: true
    url: '<WEBHOOK_URL'

    If you wanted other notification mechanisms like e-mail, PagerDuty or Slack for example you would update the ConfigMap with the correct configuration (as documented on https://prometheus.io/docs/alerting/configuration).

To test that the alerting works from your bastion SSH into one of the nodes and shut down the Atomic OpenShift Node Service (systemctl stop atomic-openshift-node).

You may want to make sure that this is not a node that is running either the Alertmanager nor the Prometheus pod (you can use oc get pod -n project -o wide to display which pods run on which nodes). Your best bet is probably an Infranode rather than a worker node because the Rocket.Chat and Prometheus pods will be distributed on most regular nodes.

After a minute or two you should see an alert with a red bar and some descriptive text in the Rocket Chat window.

You can also see the Alert in both the Prometheus and Alertmanager User Interface.

Finally you can bring the node back online (systemctl start atomic-openshift-node) and a few minutes later you should see a second notification with the same text - but with a green bar indicating that the situation has been resolved.

Cleanup

If you want to remove your monitoring environment delete the prometheus OpenShift project and the prometheus-cluster-reader cluster role-binding.

oc delete project prometheus
oc delete clusterrolebinding prometheus-cluster-reader

Installing Zabbix for Monitoring OpenShift Container Platform

Setting up Zabbix Server

The first step is to install the Zabbix Server. In this environment we will use the Bastion VM to run the Zabbix Server. Which means that your Zabbix will be on bastion.${GUID}.example.opentlc.com.

Tip
 You can find detailed installation instructions for Zabbix Server at https://www.zabbix.com/documentation/3.2/manual/installation/install_from_packages/server_installation_with_mysql

  1. Make sure you are logged into your Bastion VM as root.

  2. Add the repository for Zabbix:

    rpm -ivh http://repo.zabbix.com/zabbix/3.2/rhel/7/x86_64/zabbix-release-3.2-1.el7.noarch.rpm

  3. Now install MariaDB Server, MariaDB Client, Apache HTTP Server and Zabbix Server:

    yum repolist
yum -y install mariadb-server mariadb-client zabbix-server-mysql zabbix-web-mysql httpd
systemctl enable mariadb
systemctl start mariadb

  4. Run mysql_secure_installation to set up your MariaDB instance with recommended security settings. This will also allow you to set a root password for your database. Feel free to replace MariaDB-Root with a root password of your choice - just make sure you use the same password everywhere we need the database root password.

    mysql_secure_installation

  5. Once the script runs you will be prompted for input.

    • Enter current password for root (enter for none): Hit Enter

    • Set root password? [Y/n] Y

    • New password: MariaDB-Root

    • Re-enter new password: MariaDB-Root

    • Hit Enter to accept default on all other prompts.

  6. Now create the Zabbix Database (again feel free to replace Zabbix-Root with a password of your choice):

    mysql -uroot -pMariaDB-Root

mysql> create database zabbix character set utf8 collate utf8_bin;
mysql> grant all privileges on zabbix.* to zabbix@localhost identified by 'Zabbix-Root';
mysql> quit;

  7. Populate the newly created database with Zabbix Tables:

    zcat /usr/share/doc/zabbix-server-mysql-3.2.*/create.sql.gz | mysql -Dzabbix -uzabbix -pZabbix-Root

  8. Edit the file /etc/zabbix/zabbix_server.conf and update the following values (removing # when necessary):

    DBHost=localhost
DBName=zabbix
DBUser=zabbix
DBPassword=Zabbix-Root

  9. Zabbix requires SELinux to be turned off:

    • Edit /etc/selinux/config and change SELINUX=permissive

    • On the command line turn off SELinux for the current session:

      setenforce Permissive

  10. Update the Zabbix web frontend configuration by editing the file /etc/httpd/conf.d/zabbix.conf and update the following values if necessary - most likely this will just include removing the comment and setting the correct timezone:

    php_value max_execution_time 300
php_value memory_limit 128M
php_value post_max_size 16M
php_value upload_max_filesize 2M
php_value max_input_time 300
php_value always_populate_raw_post_data -1
php_value date.timezone America/New_York

  11. Enable and start the Zabbix Server:

    systemctl enable zabbix-server
systemctl start zabbix-server

  12. Make sure your Zabbix Server is running:

    systemctl status zabbix-server

  13. Update the Apache HTTP Server Configuration to redirect / to /zabbix by editing /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf, searching for "Redirect" and adding the following line to that section (alias_module):

    RedirectMatch ^/$ /zabbix

  14. Set SELinux Rules for Zabbix to connect to the HTTP Server and start Apache:

    setsebool -P httpd_can_connect_zabbix on
systemctl enable httpd
systemctl start httpd

  15. Make sure your Apache Server is running:

    systemctl status httpd

  16. Default Firewall Rules prohibit access to the HTTP Server port by default. Additionally Zabbix agents need access to port 10051 to automatically register themselves with the server. Therefore enable ports 80 and 10051 on the firewall.

    Edit the file /etc/sysconfig/iptables and add the following two lines after the line that accepts traffic on port 22:

    -A INPUT -p tcp -m state --state NEW -m tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
-A INPUT -p tcp -m state --state NEW -m tcp --dport 10051 -j ACCEPT

    The section should look like this:

    -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
-A INPUT -p tcp -m state --state NEW -m tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
-A INPUT -p tcp -m state --state NEW -m tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
-A INPUT -p tcp -m state --state NEW -m tcp --dport 10051 -j ACCEPT

  17. Save the file, restart the iptables service and make sure your rules are now active:

    systemctl restart iptables
iptables --list

    You should see the following output:

    Chain INPUT (policy ACCEPT)
target     prot opt source               destination
ACCEPT     all  --  anywhere             anywhere             state RELATED,ESTABLISHED
ACCEPT     icmp --  anywhere             anywhere
ACCEPT     all  --  anywhere             anywhere
ACCEPT     tcp  --  anywhere             anywhere             state NEW tcp dpt:ssh
ACCEPT     tcp  --  anywhere             anywhere             state NEW tcp dpt:http
ACCEPT     tcp  --  anywhere             anywhere             state NEW tcp dpt:zabbix-trapper
REJECT     all  --  anywhere             anywhere             reject-with icmp-host-prohibited
[...]

  18. You can now access Zabbix Server at http://bastion.$GUID.example.opentlc.com which will start the frontend configuration.

Zabbix Server Frontend Configuration

  1. Open your web browser and to go 'http://bastion.$GUID.example.opentlc.com'.

    Tip
    		 Documentation to install the Zabbix Frontend is located at https://www.zabbix.com/documentation/3.2/manual/quickstart/login

  2. Follow the prompts of the configuration wizard by clicking Next step:

    • Make sure your Zabbix DB Password is the same that we set when configuring the Zabbix Database earlier (e.g. Zabbix-Root).

    • Accept the default values for everything else and click Next step until you see the success page.

    • Click Finish. You will see the Zabbix Login page.

  3. Log in with Admin/zabbix (case sensitive) to see the Zabbix Dashboard.

Configuring Monitoring Templates

  1. Download the OCP Host Templates from Github to your local workstation:

    curl -o zabbix_ocp_templates.xml https://raw.githubusercontent.com/wkulhanek/openshift-zabbix/master/zabbix_ocp_templates.xml

  2. Click on Configuration / Templates to bring up the Templates Screen.

  3. Click Import (top right corner of the page) to import the OCP Host Templates.

  4. Click Browse and pick the templates file you just downloaded.

  5. Click Import to actually import the templates.

  6. By default the template to monitor the master API uses port 443 to check OCP master public API. If you need to change this (to port 8443 for example), Go to Configuration / Hosts / YOURMASTER / macros, click on Inherited and host macros, and change the effective value of your port from 443 to whatever it needs to be. Then click Update.

Preparing Zabbix Server for auto registration of Zabbix Agents

  1. Switch to Configuration / Actions.

  2. From the Event Source drop down in the top right corner select Auto registration.

  3. Create three actions by clicking Create action and adding the following properties:

    Tip
    		 Be careful when creating these Actions. You need to click the underlined Add link to add each of the items. Only when everything has been added should you click the blue Add button to create the item. If you accidentally click the blue button before you are finished simply open the item again and resume editing.

    Name

    Condition

    Operations

    Auto-register OCP Host

    Host Metadata like OCP Host

    Add Host; Add host to host groups: OCP Host; Link to templates: Template OS Linux - OCP Host

    Auto-register OCP Node

    Host Metadata like OCP Node

    Add Host; Add host to host groups: OCP Host; Link to templates: Template OS Linux - OCP Host, Templates OS Linux - OCP Node

    Auto-register OCP Master

    Host Metadata like OCP Master

    Add Host; Add host to host groups: OCP Host; Link to templates: Template OS Linux - OCP Host, Templates OS Linux - OCP Node, Templates OS Linux - OCP Master

    Your final configuration should look like this:

  4. Your Zabbix server is now prepared to be discovered by Zabbix agents.

  5. Switch back to the main dashboard by clicking Monitoring/Dashboard.

Install Zabbix Agents on all Nodes:

  1. On your bastion host as root clone the openshift-zabbix project. This project contains the playbooks and configuration files to set up all the Zabbix Agents on all OpenShift nodes:

    cd /root
git clone https://github.com/wkulhanek/openshift-zabbix
cd openshift-zabbix

  2. Edit the file zabbix_vars.yml and make sure that zabbix_host points to the Zabbix server you previously installed (most likely you will need to change the GUID).

  3. Run the playbook to install the Agents on all nodes:

    ansible-playbook install-zabbix-agents.yml
    Tip
    		 The playbook picks up all the hosts to install the Zabbix Agent to from the OpenShift Ansible configuration file /etc/ansible/hosts. If your Ansible hosts file is in a different location include -i /path/to/your/hosts_file as a parameter.

  4. Run the playbook to configure the Agents on all nodes:

    ansible-playbook configure-zabbix-agents.yml

  5. This includes everything necessary to deploy and configure the Zabbix Agent along with associated scripts to OpenShift nodes. Since we set up automatic discovery of Zabbix Agents in our Zabbix Server no other steps are necessary.

  6. Log into your Zabbix Server and verify that all Nodes have been automatically discovered and added to the list of monitored nodes. This may take a few minutes.

    Your dashboard should show all discovered hosts as green (without problems). And it should also show them as part of the OCP host group.:

  7. Switch to Configuration / Hosts to see details about the automatically registered OpenShift Nodes:

    Note how there is a green ZBX status indicating that the Zabbix server can communicate with the agent. Also note that there are a number of applications and triggers set up for each host.

Your Zabbix Environment is now fully configured and will monitor your environment.

Next Steps

Feel free to play around in the Zabbix Dashboard or investigate some of the templates.

In a real environment we would now set up alerting to ensure that any abnormality would immediately be reported. This could happen via e-mail, Slack, Pager, SMS or other means. In our lab environment we don’t have any of those available so we will skip this step. In case anything goes wrong an alert will be raised - it will however not be sent to any recipients but rather displayed on the Dashboard.
